<p>I have a simple table of items, called "ITEMS":</p>  <pre><code>id  description --  -----------  1  Something  2  Another thing  3  Best thing </code></pre>  <p>I have a list of Int32 which are item IDs I'd like to show:</p>  <pre><code>List&lt;Int32&gt; currentItemsCodes = new List&lt;int&gt;(); </code></pre>  <p>For this example currentItemsCodes contains 1,2,2,3</p>  <p>Currently I have this Linq-to-SQL:</p>  <pre><code>var itemDescriptions = (from a in db.ITEMS where currentItemsCodes.Contains(a.id) select new {a.id, a.description}); </code></pre>  <p>What this returns is:</p>  <pre><code>1,Something 2,Another thing 3,Best thing </code></pre>  <p>I need to return two "Another things":</p>  <pre><code>1,Something 2,Another thing 2,Another thing 3,Best thing </code></pre>  <p>Or if currentItemsCodes was 3,3,3,3 I would need 4 x "Best thing" returned</p>